// E2E tests for automatic binary→charlist coercion at the Erlang FFI boundary
// (BT-1127, BT-1398, ADR 0028 §3).
//
// Beamtalk strings are binaries (<<"hello">>). Many Erlang functions expect
// charlists ([104,101,108,108,111]). The proxy and direct-call path both
// auto-convert binary arguments to charlists on badarg, and convert charlist
// results back to binaries — including on the direct success path (BT-1398).
//
// Note: os:cmd returns a string with a trailing newline. The `_` wildcard
// suffix in the assertion matches the trailing newline character.

// ===========================================================================
// os:cmd — binary arg auto-coerced to charlist, result returned as String
// ===========================================================================

// Basic command execution with binary string arg
Erlang os cmd: "echo hello"
// => hello_

// Multi-word command
Erlang os cmd: "echo foo bar"
// => foo bar_

// ===========================================================================
// calendar:system_time_to_rfc3339 — charlist result coerced without badarg retry (BT-1398)
// ===========================================================================

// Returns charlist in Erlang, but should be auto-coerced to String
now := Erlang erlang system_time: #second
// => _
ts := Erlang calendar system_time_to_rfc3339: now
// => _
ts class name
// => String
